Advanced NumPy
copy() vs view()
copy() creates an independent copy. Changes do not affect the original.
view() shares memory with the original. Changes affect both arrays.
np.where()
Conditional operation.
Syntax: np.where(condition, true_value, false_value)
Example: np.where(arr>25,100,arr)
np.any() and np.all()
any() returns True if at least one value satisfies the condition.
all() returns True only if every value satisfies the condition.
np.unique()
Removes duplicate values.
Example: np.unique([10,20,20,30]) -> [10 20 30]
sort() vs argsort()
sort() returns sorted values.
argsort() returns indexes that would sort the array.
concatenate()
Combines arrays into one array.
vstack()
Stacks arrays vertically (row-wise).
hstack()
Stacks arrays horizontally (column-wise for 1D arrays).
split()
Splits an array into equal parts.
Real AI Usage
where() for label creation, unique() for categories, concatenate()/stack() for merging datasets, split() for batch processing.
Common Mistakes
copy() != view(). argsort() returns indexes, not values. where() can preserve original values by using arr as the false condition.
Interview Questions
1. copy vs view?
2. any vs all?
3. sort vs argsort?
4. Why unique in ML?
5. concatenate vs vstack vs hstack?
Cheat Sheet
copy() -> Copy
view() -> Shared memory
where() -> Conditional
any() -> At least one
all() -> All
unique() -> Remove duplicates
sort() -> Sorted values
argsort() -> Sorted indexes
concatenate() -> Join arrays
vstack() -> Vertical
hstack() -> Horizontal
split() -> Divide array
